\begin{document}$$ E(\theta |X_ + = v) \le E(\theta |X_ + = w),\;\;\;\;{\text{for }}0 \le v < w \le J, $$\end{document}[4]. This inequality says that as the total score increases the mean θ also increases (or stays the same). Thus, groups of patients that have higher total scores, on average also have higher latent variable values. This result may not seem spectacular at first sight, but it (1) ascertains an ordinal scale for patient measurement (2) using only observable total scores (without requiring the actual estimation of θ). For the psychological well-being example, if the MHM fits the data, ordering patients by means of the total score by implication orders them on the latent variable θ.

The relatively short WHOQOL-Bref may also be considered for use as a tool for assessing HRQoL at the individual level in clinical and medical settings. For example, the WHOQOL-Bref may be used to evaluate whether a patient’s HRQoL has improved after taking medication. An interesting feature of a fitting IRT model is that psychometric properties can be evaluated conditionally on the latent variable. For example, the measurement error of X+ can be evaluated at different values of the latent variable. TestGraf98 provides graphical information about the standard error of measurement based on the MHM model. For example, for the physical-health domain Testgraf98 estimated a standard error of measurement ranging from 2.8 for X+ ≤ 20 to 1.8 for X+ ≥ 28. Thus, to be significant at the 5% significance level differences between two observed X+ scores have to be larger than \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
