\begin{document}$$ 1.8 \times 1.96 \times \sqrt 2 \approx 5 $$\end{document} for X+ ≥ 28 (e.g., see [44], p. 209). This is a substantial standard error of measurement relative to the length of scale. This relatively large measurement error appears to be consistent with the observed Hj values, which indicate weak to moderate scalability. For the other three content domains, the standard error of measurement was also substantial. Thus, caution has to be exercised when drawing conclusions about differences and changes in individual levels of HRQoL based on observed X+ scores from the WHOQOL-Bref and any other HRQOL measure—see [45].
